%I A395258 #23 Apr 27 2026 19:26:00
%S A395258 15,45,69,99,105,165,195,231,315,441,465,501,615,645,675,759,771,825,
%T A395258 879,909,969,1095,1215,1425,1449,1491,1551,1581,1599,1665,1695,1785,
%U A395258 1869,2001,2139,2241,2349,2391,2475,2541,2661,2751,2799,2835,2859,2955,3021,3039,3165,3219,3255
%N A395258 Numbers k such that k-2 and k+2 are prime and gcd(k, sigma(k)) is prime.
%C A395258 k is the midpoint of a cousin prime pair (k-2, k+2); this sequence is a subsequence of A087679.
%C A395258 All terms are congruent to 3 mod 6, hence divisible by 3. Among the three integers k-2, k, k+2 exactly one is divisible by 3, and since k-2 and k+2 are prime, it must be k.
%C A395258 Among the computed terms, gcd(k, sigma(k)) = 3 occurs most frequently.
%e A395258 For k = 15: k-2 = 13 and k+2 = 17 are prime. Also, sigma(15) = 24 and gcd(15, 24) = 3, which is prime, so 15 is a term.
%e A395258 For k = 5: k-2 = 3 and k+2 = 7 are prime, but sigma(5) = 6 and gcd(5, 6) = 1, which is not prime, so 5 is not a term.
%p A395258 filter:= k -> isprime(k-2) and isprime(k+2) and isprime(igcd(k,NumberTheory:-sigma(k))):
%p A395258 select(filter, [seq(i,i=3..10000,6)]); # _Robert Israel_, Apr 22 2026
%t A395258 Select[Range[3000], And @@ PrimeQ[{# - 2, # + 2, GCD[#, DivisorSigma[1, #]]}] &] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Apr 17 2026 *)
%o A395258 (Python)
%o A395258 from sympy import divisor_sigma, gcd, isprime
%o A395258 def ok(k): return isprime(k-2) and isprime(k+2) and isprime(gcd(k, divisor_sigma(k)))
%o A395258 print([k for k in range(1, 3000) if ok(k)])
%Y A395258 Intersection of A087679 and A392199.
%K A395258 nonn,new
%O A395258 1,1
%A A395258 _Aied Sulaiman_, Apr 17 2026
